<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-416-588  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 416 588.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  April 30 1990 v9 n9 p8(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CFO action delayed as Congress awaits administration consensus.andO;(Chief Financial Officer)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Grimm, Vanessa Jo.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. CongressFinancial OfficersLegislationFinancial AnalysisUnited States. Office of Management and BudgetUnited States. Department of the Treasury.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>CFO Action Delayed as Congress Awaits Administration ConsensusandM;Sen.andP;  John Glenn has delayed indefinitely action on a proposal to mandate achief financial officer in the government, because key players cannot agreeif the position should be within the Office of Management and Budget or theTreasury Department.andM;Glenn had hoped to offer his bill by the end of March and then hold a seriesof hearings on the CFO legislation.andP;  The Ohio Democrat and chairman of theSenate Governmental Affairs Committee had been told even President Bushsupported his plan.andM;But now a slight rift appears to have emerged.andP;  OMB Director Richard Darmanand Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady agree on the need for a mandatoryCFO position, but a committee staff member said they cannot see eye to eye onthe best location for the new job.andP;  OMB has a chief financial officer as partof its staff now.andM;Former OMB Director Joseph R. Wright Jr.andP;  created that position in 1987.andP;  ButGlenn and others say the job needs the clout of congressional mandate.andM;Glenn does not want to sponsor his bill without complete administrationconsensus, a staff member said, and he is prodding the White House foraction.andM;The committee's majority members already are deadlocked with OMB overreauthorization of OMB's Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs.andP;  Glennwould like to see the CFO proposal clear the Congress and be signed swiftlyby the president, the staff member said.andM;Although both Darman and Brady have spoken publicly about the government'sneed to improve its financial house, they have kept mum on the issue lately.andO;</TEXT></DOC>